===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} Sense; meaning; significance.
#* Milton
#*: The discourse itself, voluble enough, and full of '''sentence'''.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} One's [[opinion]]; manner of thinking. {{defdate|14th-17th c.}}
#* Milton
#*: My '''sentence''' is for open war.
# {{context|now|_|rare|lang=en}} A [[pronounced]] opinion or [[judgment]] on a given question. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#* Atterbury
#*: By them [Luther's works] we may pass '''sentence''' upon his doctrines.
# {{context|dated|lang=en}} The decision or [[judgement]] of a jury or court; a [[verdict]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#: ''The court returned a '''sentence''' of guilt in the first charge, but innocence in the second.''
# The judicial order for a [[punishment]] to be imposed on a person convicted of a [[crime]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#: ''The judge declared a '''sentence''' of death by hanging for the infamous cattle rustler.''
#* '''1900''', {{w|Charles W. Chesnutt}}, ''{{w|The House Behind the Cedars}}'', Chapter I,
#*: The murderer, he recalled, had been tried and sentenced to imprisonment for life, but was pardoned by a merciful governor after serving a year of his '''sentence'''.
# A punishment imposed on a person convicted of a crime.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} A [[saying]], especially form a great person; a [[maxim]], an [[apophthegm]]. {{defdate|14th-19th c.}}
#* {{RQ:Flr Mntgn Essays}}, I.40:
#*: Men (saith an ancient Greek '''sentence''') are tormented by the opinions they have of things, and not by things themselves.
#: {{rfquotek|Broome}}
# {{context|grammar|lang=en}} A grammatically complete series of words consisting of a [[subject]] and [[predicate]], even if one or the other is implied, and typically beginning with a [[capital letter]] and ending with a [[full stop]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#: ''The children were made to construct '''sentences''' consisting of nouns and verbs from the list on the chalkboard.''
# {{context|logic|lang=en}} A [[formula]] with no [[free variable]]s. {{defdate|from 20th c.}}
# {{context|computing theory|lang=en}} Any of the set of [[string]]s that can be generated by a given [[formal grammar]]. {{defdate|from 20th c.}}

